Am 02-Jan-00 schrieb Micha!?:

>Hello, Hans-Joerg

>On 01-Jan-00 dared Hans-Joerg Frieden to write:

>> On Thu, 30 Dec 1999, Alan Lee Maurice Buxey wrote:
>> 
>>> hmm, what sort of fogging does flightgear require then?
>> Fogging is not really a problem. I would suspect that it uses EXP or
>> EXP_2, as this mimics atmospheric hazing. This can be emulated by linear
>> fogging.

Just a little note to this one: exp fogging surely can be emulated by
linear fogging, but that's currently not supported by the 3D drivers,
and it's IMHO quite complicated and would require to subdivide all
polygons. Second, none of the currently available 3d hardware for
AMIGA even supports linear fogging. Basically none of these hardware
supports any GL-compliant fogging. All the Virge and Permedia2 do is
interpolate a fog value in linear space, but that's really far away from
linear fogging, which interpolates the fog value in Z direction (the
difference can be best seen in the 'rollercoaster' demo with and without
hardware acceleration). Actually most 3d hardware which support these
fogging types use tables to approximate the theoretical fog function.

>Emulated in a way, that it looks almost like that other fogging modes??
>I've already tried the other foggings in QMapGL, but then it works just 
>without 3D-HW.

IIRC there is some variable which allows the 3d drivers to use another
fogging type as replacement for exp fogging. Otherwise the 3d driver
rejects accelerated fogging, because it's not accurate enough.

bye
