Hi,

On 13 Jan 2000, Tom Miles wrote:
> So does the BVision support zbuffering or what?

Yup.

> When I call W3D_AllocateZBuffer() it returns with a success, but no matter
> what value I put in ZCompareMode it still draws absolutely nothing when I
> enable the ZBuffer state!  This is also very apparent in WarpTest as
> whichever mode I select the shape doesn't get drawn.  I'm also somewhat
> confused as to the necessity of the various read & write zpixel functions.
> Does warp3d actually do all the calculations for you or not?

Normally, you'll have to do two things to use the Z-Buffer: Allocate it
(you did that), and clear it to an appropriate value. For "normal"
Z-Buffer operation, you would clear to 1.0 (which is the far plane), and
set the compare mode to LESS or LEQUAL. Then, off course, the Z
coordinates you put into your vertex structure msut be sane, or you won't
see anything.

Concerning WarpTest: You can push the Z-Buffer clear value around with
some keys (was it +/- on the num-pad ?). If you set it to around 0.7, you
should be able to see the effect by rotating and moving the plane. If not:
Oups!

The Z-Buffer read/write functions, btw, are only used to manually access
the Z-Buffer or write stuff into it. You can for instance use the
information to find the z-depth of a pixel on screen. Some ego-shooters
use this (Half-Life, IIRC).

