@node 08055.010
Subject: Re: John Carmack speaks
From: Peter McGavin <P.McGavin@irl.cri.nz>
Date: Fri, 21 Jan 2000 12:11:55 +1300 (NZDT)

>Here is a little aritice that is based on an interview with John
>Carmack, coder of the Doom and Quake series amoung others. I finally got
>some OCR software for my miggy and so scanned it in.
>[...]
>Comments?

Thanks, it was an interesting read.

It seems that people, including John Carmack, often talk about "the
CPU" and "the 3D accelerator".  That is an accurate description of
most current gaming platforms, but I see no reason why it should
always be like that.  The Amiga was one of the first architectures to
separate 2D graphics functions from the CPU.  It took at least 5 years
for CPU speeds to increase sufficiently for this separation to become
unnecessary.  Now 3D rendering is separated on most popular gaming
platforms, I wonder how long that will last.  CPU speeds are still
doubling every 18 months or so, like they have been since before 1970,
with no sign of stopping soon.

Perhaps dedicated graphics processors will eventually be replaced with
general purpose CPUs.  That eliminates the problems that occur when
the graphics accelerator doesn't support a particular gfx effect you
want.  On the other hand, people have been predicting multiple general
purpose CPU architectures for decades, and they have yet to happen in
a popular platform.  Dual CPU pentiums are available for reasonable
cost now, but the 2nd CPU is still too slow compared with a dedicated
3D processor.  And you can either pay a bit more or wait 18 months to
get a single CPU that's twice as fast.  A major issue is the best way
to connect multiple CPUs together.  If they are too closely coupled,
contention slows them both down.  If they are too separated,
communication becomes a bottleneck.  Instead of multiple CPUs, chip
manufacturers are currently building parallelism into their CPUs at a
very low level in the form of super scalar capability and multiple
execution units.

Anyway, that's my 2c.
--
Peter McGavin.   (p.mcgavin@irl.cri.nz)
