> drivers made, or would I have to talk one of my more
> software-knowledgable friends into doing the driver? Thanks. Again,
> this is all about 6 months away at least...

The most important thing is to get decent documentation for the chip you
want to use. Everything else is relatively "unimportant". With the recent
open release of the Voodoo documentation, this would be a good idea. Or,
alternatively, the Linux GLX drivers for the nVidia chips are available in
source code form, so this would alos be of help. 

If that is available, building a hardware driver for Warp3D wouldn't be
too much of a problem. I'm assuming most modern chips have setup stages,
so the nightmare with the gradient-calculation-infected Virge driver
wouldn't repeat. For someone wanting to do a driver, we have a driver sdk
that we would make available. It contains a skeleton driver where you more
or less "fill the gaps" (of course, these gaps may be *huge* :)

